Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Chapter 2  -  Section 2.1", "Title"],

Cell[TextData[{
  StyleBox["In this ",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  StyleBox[" notebook, you will continue to draw direction fields for \
differential equations and use these to explore the impact of initial \
conditions on the behavior of solutions to the differential equations. ",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  "\n\n",
  StyleBox["In most cases, to adapt this code to other problems, you will \
have to change only the input shown in red. To open a cell grouping, \
double-click on the right-hand side of the double cell marker.",
    FontSize->14]
}], "Subsubtitle"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
  "Problem",
  " 21:   y' - ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(TraditionalForm\`1\/2\)]],
  "y = 2 Cos[t]"
}], "Section"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Drawing Direction Field and Exploring Solutions Graphically", \
"Subsection"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "As in Chapter 1, in order to execute the ",
  StyleBox["PlotVectorField",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  " command, we must first load a graphics package."
}], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(<< Graphics`PlotField`\)], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
We will begin by defining the derivative as a function of y and t. You may \
ignore the warning messages about the possible spelling errors here.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{\(Clear[y, t]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"yprime", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(\(1\/2\) y\  + 2  Cos[t]\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"tmin", "=", 
        StyleBox["0",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"tmax", "=", 
        StyleBox["20",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ymin", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(-10\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ymax", "=", 
        StyleBox["10",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], 
      ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(pd = 
      PlotVectorField[{1, yprime}, {t, tmin, tmax}, {y, ymin, ymax}, \ 
        Axes \[Rule] True, AxesLabel \[Rule] {t, y}, ScaleFactor \[Rule] 4, 
        AspectRatio \[Rule] 1]\)}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
If you want to enlarge your plot,highlight the plot and drag the right-hand \
side out.The arrows get longer as the value of the derivative gets larger.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
You might notice that solutions with starting values in the positive range \
will tend to approach positive infinity as t \[Rule] \[Infinity], whereas \
solutions with starting values in the negative range might lead you to \
negative infinity. We will find the analytical solution to analyze this more \
carefully.\
\>", "Text"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["General Solution of the Differential Equation", "Subsection"],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
      "Noting", " ", "that", " ", "the", " ", "integrating", " ", "factor", 
        " ", "for", " ", "this", " ", "linear", " ", "differential", " ", 
        "equation", " ", "is", " ", 
        StyleBox[\(\[ExponentialE]\^\(\(-t\)/2\)\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ",", 
      " ", \(we\ can\ write\ the\ solution\ in\ integral\ form\ and\ let\ \
Mathematica\ do\ the\ \(\(integration\)\(.\)\)\)}]], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{\(Clear[c1]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{\(ygenl[t_, c1_]\), "=", 
      RowBox[{
        RowBox[{
          StyleBox[\(\[ExponentialE]\^\(t/2\)\),
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
          StyleBox[" ",
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
          RowBox[{
            StyleBox["(",
              FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
            RowBox[{
              
              StyleBox[\(2 \(\[Integral]\[ExponentialE]\^\(\(-t\)/2\)\ Cos[
                        t] \[DifferentialD]t\)\),
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], " ", "+", " ", "c1"}], ")"}]}],
         "//", "Simplify"}]}]}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
We can see from this general solution that the first term involving the \
arbitrary constant is the one that will dramatically impact the behavior of \
our solution as t \[Rule] \[Infinity]. The Cosine and Sine terms will always \
be there, but these do not cause our solution to go to infinity. To eliminate \
the term that approaches infinity, we will need to set c1 equal to 0. \
Therefore the initial condition that separates the transition from one type \
of behavior to another can easily be determined.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    RowBox[{"ygenl", "[", 
      RowBox[{"t", ",", 
        StyleBox["0",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{"acritical", "=", 
      RowBox[{"ygenl", "[", 
        RowBox[{"0", ",", 
          StyleBox["0",
            FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "]"}]}]}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
We can see that this solution is periodic and bounded both above and below. \
We will plot this solution curve together with others nearby. We will draw \
these curves a bit thicker so they will stand out when plotted with the \
direction field.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{"pc", "=", 
      RowBox[{"Plot", "[", 
        RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"{", 
            RowBox[{
              RowBox[{"ygenl", "[", 
                RowBox[{"t", ",", 
                  StyleBox["0",
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "]"}], ",", 
              RowBox[{"ygenl", "[", 
                RowBox[{"t", ",", 
                  StyleBox[\(- .5\),
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "]"}], ",", 
              RowBox[{"ygenl", "[", 
                RowBox[{"t", ",", 
                  StyleBox[".5",
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "]"}], ",", 
              RowBox[{"ygenl", "[", 
                RowBox[{"t", ",", 
                  StyleBox[\(-1\),
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "]"}], ",", 
              RowBox[{"ygenl", "[", 
                RowBox[{"t", ",", 
                  StyleBox["1",
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "]"}]}], "}"}], 
          ",", \({t, tmin, tmax}\), ",", \(PlotRange \[Rule] {ymin, ymax}\), 
          ",", \(PlotStyle \[Rule] {{Thickness[0.01]}}\)}], "]"}]}]], "Input"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Direction Field with Solution Curves", "Subsection"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(Show[pd, pc, PlotRange \[Rule] {ymin, ymax}]\)], "Input"]
}, Closed]]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
